   "source": [
    "# Singular Value Decomposition"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Understanding SVD\n",
    "\n",
    "- SVD is a matrix factorization method.\n",
    "- basically it rotates, streches and rotates the data for various methods.(we'll see it later)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$X = U \\Sigma V^T$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Full SVD\n",
    "\n",
    "$X_{m \\times n} = U_{m \\times m} \\Sigma_{m \\times n} V^T_{n \\times n}$\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "    x_1 && x_2 && ... && x_n\\\\\n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}\\\\=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "    u_1 && u_2 && .. && u_m\\\\\n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times m}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    \\sigma_1 && 0 && 0 && 0 \\\\\n",
    "    0 && \\sigma_2 && 0 && 0 \\\\\n",
    "    && ... \\\\\n",
    "    0 && 0 && ... && \\sigma_n \\\\\n",
    "    0 && 0 && ... && 0\\\\\n",
    "    0 && 0 && ... && 0\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    -- && v_1^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "    -- && v_2^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "       && ... \\\\\n",
    "    -- && v_n^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times n}$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Economy SVD\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "$X_{m \\times n} = U_{m \\times n} \\Sigma_{n \\times n} V^T_{n \\times n}$\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "    x_1 && x_2 && ... && x_n\\\\\n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}\\\\=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "    u_1 && u_2 && .. && u_n\\\\\n",
    "    | && | && && | \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    \\sigma_1 && 0 && 0 && 0 \\\\\n",
    "    0 && \\sigma_2 && 0 && 0 \\\\\n",
    "    && ... \\\\\n",
    "    0 && 0 && ... && \\sigma_n\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times n}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix} \n",
    "    -- && v_1^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "    -- && v_2^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "       && ... \\\\\n",
    "    -- && v_n^T && -- \\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times n}$\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "$X = \\sigma_1 u_1 v_1^T + \\sigma_1 u_1 v_1^T + ... + \\sigma_n u_n v_n^T + 0 = \\hat{U} \\hat{\\Sigma} \\hat{V}^T$\n",
    "[Till m ranks]\n",
    "[So actually here you just need to take m columns from U matrix because rest of them will automatically be multiplied with 0 from $\\Sigma$. It is called an economy SVD]\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "### Properties\n",
    "\n",
    "- $U^T U = U U^T = I_{m \\times m}$\n",
    "- $V^T V = V V^T = I_{n \\times n}$\n",
    "(i.e. U and V are `orthogonal`, unitary matrices)\n",
    "- $\\Sigma$ is heirarchically ordered ranks $\\sigma_1 \\geq \\sigma_2 \\geq ... \\geq \\sigma_n \\geq 0$ . Ordered by importance.\n",
    "- the columns of U are the Left singular vectors.\n",
    "- $\\Sigma$ (the same dimensions as A) has singular values and is `diagonal`.\n",
    "- and $V^T$ has rows that are the Right singular vectors. The SVD represents an expansion of the original data in a coordinate system where the covariance matrix is diagonal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "```\n",
    "_____________________    __________ ______________________\n",
    "|                   |    |        ||                     |\n",
    "|                   |    |        ||          V^T        |\n",
    "|                   |    |        ||_____________________|\n",
    "|                   |    |        | \\\n",
    "|         X         |  = |   U    |  \\\n",
    "|                   |    |        |   \\ Sigma\n",
    "|                   |    |        |    \\\n",
    "|                   |    |        |     \\\n",
    "|___________________|    |________|      \\\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Explore with numpy"
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {},

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Eckart-Young Theorem (Low rank approximation)\n",
    "\n",
    "Best approximation of X = $\\tilde{X}$ (X tilde)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "${{argmin}\\atop{{\\tilde{X} such.that. rank(\\tilde{X}) = r}}} {|| X - \\tilde{X} ||}_F = \\tilde{U}\\tilde{\\Sigma}\\tilde{V}^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "F = The Frobenius norm, sometimes also called the Euclidean norm (a term unfortunately also used for the vector -norm), is matrix norm of an matrix defined as the square root of the sum of the absolute squares of its elements."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "rank r means selecting only \n",
    "- r columns of u\n",
    "- r rows of $v^T$\n",
    "- and $\\sigma$ only till r "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\tilde{U}^T\\tilde{U} = I_{r \\times r}$ it is still an (r x r) identity matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\tilde{U}^T\\tilde{U} \\ne I_{m \\times m}$ but not (m x m)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Below we are calculating approximations with rank r and Frobenius norm(Euclidean distances of the vectors, or as I understood rmse)"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "## SVD and Correlations\n",
    "\n",
    "`This is an interpretation of SVD. Not a very good computation method`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$X^TX=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    -- && x_1^T && --\\\\\n",
    "    -- && x_2^T && --\\\\\n",
    "    && .\\\\\n",
    "    && .\\\\\n",
    "    -- && x_n^T && --\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times m}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    | && | &&  && |\\\\\n",
    "    x_1 && x_2 && ... && x_n\\\\\n",
    "    | && | &&  && |\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    x_1^T x_1 && x_1^T x_2 && ... && x_1^T x_n\\\\\n",
    "    x_2^T x_1 && x_2^T x_2 && ... && x_2^T x_n\\\\\n",
    "    . && . && ... && .\\\\\n",
    "    x_n^T x_1 && x_n^T x_2 && ... && x_n^T x_n\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times n}$\n",
    "\n",
    "`here we are calculating product of columns actually. observe the first row of the left matrix is actually the column of the original matrix and by matrix multiplication it is getting multiplied to the first column of the right matrix`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "if \n",
    "$X = U \\Sigma V^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "then \n",
    "$X^T = V \\Sigma U^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "$X^T X = V \\Sigma U^T U \\Sigma V^T = V \\Sigma^2 V^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "multiplying V both sides\n",
    "\n",
    "$X^T X V = V \\Sigma^2$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$XX^T=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    | && | &&  && |\\\\\n",
    "    x_1 && x_2 && ... && x_n\\\\\n",
    "    | && | &&  && |\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times n}\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    -- && x_1^T && --\\\\\n",
    "    -- && x_2^T && --\\\\\n",
    "    && .\\\\\n",
    "    && .\\\\\n",
    "    -- && x_n^T && --\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{n \\times m}=\n",
    "\\begin{bmatrix}\n",
    "    x_1x_1^T  && x_2 x_1^T  && ... && x_1^T x_m\\\\\n",
    "    x_2^T x_1 && x_2 x_2^T  && ... && x_2^T x_m\\\\\n",
    "    . && . && ... && .\\\\\n",
    "    x_m^T x_1 && x_2 x_m^T && ... && x_m^T x_m\\\\\n",
    "\\end{bmatrix}_{m \\times m}$\n",
    "\n",
    "`here we are calculating product of rows`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$X X^T = U \\Sigma V^T V \\Sigma U^T  = U \\Sigma^2 U^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "multiplying U both sides\n",
    "$X^T X U = U \\Sigma^2$\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\Sigma^2$ = Eigen Values\\\n",
    "U,V = Eigen Vectors\n",
    "\n",
    "Now using this explanation to calculate SVD"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "## Method of Snapshots (SVD using eigen values and vectors)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- for U\n",
    "    - calculate X * $X^T$\n",
    "    - calculate eigen values and vectors\n",
    "    - U = eigen vectors of X * $X^T$\n",
    "\n",
    "- for V\n",
    "    - calculate $X^T$ * X\n",
    "    - calculate eigen values and vectors\n",
    "    - V = eigen vectors of $X^T$ * X"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x_xT = x @ x.T\n",
    "U_values, U = np.linalg.eig(x_xT)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "## SVD and Image Compression\n",
    "\n",
    "In simple words choosing lowest rank index(ranks are in descending order) required to generate a close approximation original matrix."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

   "source": [
    "## Log and Cumulative plots\n",
    "\n",
    "- log plot will show to keep the first few ranks and throw rest of them as thier rank/ importance is not that much.\n",
    "- cumulative plots purpose is to see that at what rank what percentage of the original matrix values(energy) is getting covered.\\\n",
    "    on x axis = ranks\\\n",
    "    on y axis = $\\frac{\\sum_{i=0}^{r}{\\sigma_i}}{\\sum_{i=0}^{m}{\\sigma_i}}$    \n",
    "- to pick up a rank where we can get maximum energy possible"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 63,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

    "ax[1].plot(np.cumsum(s)/np.sum(s),'k.-')"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "we can see around at rank 100, approx 90% original matrix is recovered."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 64,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def calc_c_mat(u,s,vT,r):\n",
    "    return u[:,:r] @ np.diag(s)[:r,:r] @ vT[:r]\n",
    "\n",
    "def calc_cum_enery_percentage(s,r):\n",
    "    return np.sum(s[:r])/np.sum(s)\n",
    "\n",
    "def rmse(x,x_bar):\n",
    "    return np.sqrt(np.square(x - x_bar).sum())"
   ]
  },
